{"id":"2204.10651","submitter":"Beibei Liu","authors":"Beibei Liu, Anders Johansen, Michiel Lambrechts, Martin Bizzarro and\n  Troels Haugb{\\o}lle","title":"Natural separation of two primordial planetary reservoirs in an\n  expanding solar protoplanetary disk","comments":"Authors' version, 13 pages, 4 figures. Published in Science Advances\n  in the issue of April 22, 2022","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.EP astro-ph.SR","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Meteorites display an isotopic composition dichotomy between non-carbonaceous\n(NC) and carbonaceous (CC) groups, indicating that planetesimal formation in\nthe solar protoplanetary disk occurred in two distinct reservoirs. The\nprevailing view is that a rapidly formed Jupiter acted as a barrier between\nthese reservoirs. We show a fundamental inconsistency in this model: if Jupiter\nis an efficient blocker of drifting pebbles, then the interior NC reservoir is\ndepleted by radial drift within a few hundred thousand years. If Jupiter lets\nmaterial pass it, then the two reservoirs will be mixed. Instead, we\ndemonstrate that the arrival of the CC pebbles in the inner disk is delayed for\nseveral million years by the viscous expansion of the protoplanetary disk. Our\nresults support that Jupiter formed in the outer disk (>10 AU) and allowed a\nconsiderable amount of CC material to pass it and become accreted by the\nterrestrial planets.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 22 Apr 2022 11:42:55 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-04-25"}
